response:
 First, let's have a look at this expression:
\begin{aligned}
\left( \sqrt{100} - \sqrt{36} \right)^2.
\end{aligned}
We meet this kind of task a lot. According to the square of a difference, the value of $$\left( \sqrt{100} - \sqrt{36} \right)^2$$ equals to
\begin{aligned}
\left( \sqrt{100} \right)^2 - 2\sqrt{100}\sqrt{36} + \left( \sqrt{36} \right)^2.
\end{aligned}
It is easy to calculate the answer. The square root is to find the number that is multiplied by itself to get the original number. In this task, $$\sqrt{100} = 10$$ and $$\sqrt{36} = 6.$$ Therefore,
\begin{aligned}
\left( \sqrt{100} - \sqrt{36} \right)^2 &= \left( 10 - 6 \right)^2 \\
&= 4^2 \\
&= 16.
\end{aligned}

